CRM GOVERNANCE BOARD MODEL
Purpose:
Ensure all CRM changes are aligned, controlled, prioritized, and scalable
 1. GOVERNANCE OBJECTIVES
•	Align CRM with business strategy 
•	Control scope creep and random requests 
•	Improve quality and consistency 
•	Reduce risk (technical + operational) 
•	Prioritize high-value initiatives 
 In simple terms:
“Nothing enters CRM without structure, review, and alignment.”
 2. GOVERNANCE BOARD STRUCTURE
Core Members (Mandatory)
Role	Responsibility
CRM Lead (You)	Own governance, technical authority
Product Owner / Business Lead	Defines priorities
IT / Architecture Lead	Ensures technical alignment
QA / Testing Lead	Quality control
Data/Integration Lead	Data integrity & integrations

Optional Members (as needed)
•	Security/Compliance (for regulated environments) 
•	Finance (for cost-impact decisions) 
•	Sales/Operations SMEs 
 3. GOVERNANCE OPERATING MODEL
Weekly Governance Meeting (30–60 min)
Agenda:
1.	New Requests Intake Review 
2.	Priority Alignment 
3.	Technical Feasibility Review 
4.	Risk & Impact Assessment 
5.	Approval / Rejection Decisions 
Monthly Strategic Review
•	Roadmap alignment 
•	Performance metrics 
•	Tech debt review 
•	Major initiative planning 
 4. INTAKE PROCESS (CRITICAL)
Rule:
❌ No direct dev requests
✅ All requests go through intake
Intake Form Must Include:
•	Business objective 
•	Expected outcome 
•	Priority level 
•	Impacted users 
•	Deadline (if any) 
Request Flow:
1.	Business submits request 
2.	CRM Lead reviews (initial triage) 
3.	Governance Board evaluates 
4.	Approved → backlog 
5.	Rejected → documented reason 
 5. PRIORITIZATION FRAMEWORK
Use a simple scoring model:
Criteria	Score
Business Impact	High / Medium / Low
Revenue Impact	High / Medium / Low
Effort	High / Medium / Low
Risk	High / Medium / Low

Decision Logic:
•	High Impact + Low Effort → PRIORITY 
•	Low Impact + High Effort → DEFER 
 6. CHANGE CLASSIFICATION MODEL
Categorize all requests:
Type	Examples
Enhancement	New fields, UI improvements
Bug Fix	System issues
Integration	API, data sync
Compliance	Security, audit changes
Tech Debt	Cleanup, refactoring

 7. APPROVAL TIERS
Tier 1 (Fast Track)
•	Small changes 
•	No architectural impact
 Approved by CRM Lead 

Tier 2 (Standard)
•	Medium complexity
 Governance Board approval 
Tier 3 (Strategic)
•	Large initiatives / integrations
 Executive approval required 
 8. ARCHITECTURE REVIEW GATE
Before development starts:
Must validate:
•	Fits architecture framework 
•	No duplication of logic 
•	Proper tool usage (Plugin vs Flow vs JS) 
9. METRICS GOVERNANCE TRACKS
Track these monthly:
•	Number of requests submitted 
•	Approval vs rejection rate 
•	Delivery time 
•	Production issues 
•	Tech debt backlog size 

Why Governance 
A CRM Governance Board isn’t just “process”—it works because it fixes the exact failure points most Dynamics 365 environments run into: chaos, duplication, slow delivery, and misalignment with the business.
Here’s why it actually works in practice 👇

🎯 1. It Creates a Single Source of Truth for Decisions
Without governance:
•	Requests come from emails, Teams, hallway conversations 
•	Developers pick up work randomly 
•	Priorities constantly shift 
With governance:
•	Every request goes through one structured intake 
•	Every decision is visible and documented 
👉 Result:
No confusion about what is being built or why

⚖️ 2. It Forces Business–IT Alignment
Most CRM failures happen because:
•	Business asks for features without understanding impact 
•	IT builds solutions without understanding business value 
The board forces both sides to sit together and answer:
•	What problem are we solving? 
•	What’s the business impact? 
•	Is this the best way to solve it? 
👉 Result:
You stop building “nice-to-have” features and focus on real value

🚦 3. It Prioritizes the Right Work (Not the Loudest Voice)
Without governance:
•	The loudest stakeholder wins 
•	Urgent ≠ Important 
With governance:
•	Requests are scored objectively (impact, effort, risk) 
•	Decisions are data-driven, not emotional 
👉 Result:
High-impact work gets delivered first

🧱 4. It Prevents System Chaos & Technical Debt
This is huge in Dynamics 365.
Without governance:
•	Duplicate fields, tables, and logic 
•	Multiple flows doing the same thing 
•	Plugins + flows + JS overlapping 
With governance:
•	Every change goes through architecture review 
•	Standards are enforced before development starts 
👉 Result:
Clean, scalable system (not a patchwork CRM)

⚡ 5. It Speeds Up Delivery (Yes, really)
It may feel like governance slows things down—but it does the opposite.
Without governance:
•	Rework 
•	Miscommunication 
•	Broken releases 
With governance:
•	Clear requirements upfront 
•	Fewer surprises 
•	Less rework 
👉 Result:
Faster, smoother delivery

🧪 6. It Improves Quality & Reduces Production Issues
Because governance enforces:
•	Testing 
•	UAT sign-off 
•	Release validation 
👉 Result:
•	Fewer bugs 
•	More stable releases 
•	Higher user trust 

🔐 7. It Reduces Risk (Technical + Business)
Especially important in regulated environments.
Without governance:
•	Uncontrolled changes 
•	Security gaps 
•	Data integrity issues 
With governance:
•	Controlled approvals 
•	Security review when needed 
•	Data rules enforced 
👉 Result:
•	Lower compliance risk 
•	Better audit readiness 

📊 8. It Gives Leadership Visibility & Control
Leadership doesn’t care about plugins or flows—they care about:
•	ROI 
•	Risk 
•	Delivery speed 
Governance provides:
•	Clear backlog 
•	Prioritized roadmap 
•	Metrics (delivery time, defects, value) 
👉 Result:
Leadership sees CRM as a strategic asset, not a black box

👥 9. It Creates Accountability
Without governance:
•	“Who built this?” → nobody knows 
•	“Why was this done?” → unclear 
With governance:
•	Every request has: 
o	Owner 
o	Approval 
o	Documentation 
👉 Result:
Clear ownership across the system

🧠 10. It Transforms CRM from Tool → Platform
This is the real goal.
Without governance:
•	CRM = ticket system 
•	Constant firefighting 
With governance:
•	CRM = strategic platform 
•	Planned growth 
•	Scalable architecture 
👉 Result:
You move from reactive support → strategic leadership

🔥 The Bottom Line
A CRM Governance Board works because it enforces:
1. Clarity
Everyone knows what’s being built and why
2. Control
No random or risky changes
3. Consistency
Standards are followed every time
4. Alignment
Business and IT move together
5. Accountability
Decisions are owned and tracked


